 modern JDK's FactoryFinder might contain jdk.xml.internal.SecuritySupport. I can try using Class.forName to load javax.xml.parsers.SecuritySupport from the classpath, even if the package isn't present in the module. Testing this can confirm if I can access the package-private class. I also wonder if reflection metadata might be required for dynamic coverage in native images. It seems like I have a bit of troubleshooting to do!\\n\\n**Exploring GraalVM native test build**\\n\\nI’m looking into whether the GraalVM native test build can utilize agent-generated configs. It seems the Gradle plugin typically runs the `test` with the agent before `metadataCopy` and then `nativeCompile`. This setup could capture reflection metadata. I can check if dynamic access coverage is reported by the JVM agent; it might show up in the build reports. I wonder if I can instantiate the base class reflectively or if I should explore using public APIs instead. There's a lot to unravel!\\n\\n**Understanding custom classloader behavior**\\n\\nI'm considering what happens if a custom classloader hides SecuritySupport12. It looks like a NoClassDefFoundError would occur since that's an error and not an exception, leading to static initialization failure. If the custom classloader denies access to java.security.AccessController, Class.forName may throw a ClassNotFoundException. Custom loaders may need to override loadClass, and I’m curious whether the parent classloader could still define it. I need to think this through to get a clearer understanding!\\n\\n**Considering Gradle tests**\\n\\nI'm looking into how resources are handled in Gradle tests. Should they be on the system classloader? Or is modern JUnit relying on the app classloader? When it comes to native images, I wonder if resources need to be included and how the resource metadata comes into play. It's interesting to think that the agent is supposed to detect these details. There's a lot to unpack here!\\n\\n**Considering class modifications**\\n\\nIt looks like I have a class that isn’t public, which violates the rule that all top-level test classes must be public. Right now, it has a placeholder that's package-private. If I want to modify it, I’ll need to either fix it or remove it. I could replace the file with a dedicated test, but the mapping indicates it's for SecuritySupportTest. Should I delete XmlParserAPIsTest using bash rm instead? And, maybe I don't need AssertJ—I'll just go with JUnit assertions.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_03505b97eae3fcb30169f8cf4c82448190895600f022cf1133\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-M9klE72SFAZMD_6JXORK0w_UnqCTuxcA_QTRaPJpCHhF8vM_niqYgXqt7vnEsKe9uA3uP2wcV29SN7AhB_X0itiMyuSbxYU4TpRkxxJ4yNLSeED2JL8CEd51sgQBcS6wRYwXALqYo2ZlbJcb0BjqSLf-BRdcTJw9HHQ1XWmw2d1dMw5uBO9Syh_OlMR0rU4U02Kai3TkIJNsO9ZT7mEw0bSRk7IaiSdmRpBnI586W6CdKSNAAi32ay8NF_GvVidArFDPYZfYtNfiY5exfcC6ir-ywMpGxVTUO4Xe76yLYtyXiqrj7NuN1FGFkcOLY3vgAoQ7OiUoVGgagrrQ9F7spToIOG3DqIcdVdr3P8QiYAxEmO5DLCXxNBfHHNr3fcyOom3QM-a9oB4zrD949wHHST_AzmXQHljzxWRy7SuiMxbh_-UB2r9HnqIyrF06y28nMSwrdlVPrECPvKEyZD5ubPEvqS_7XEnHwhVxOuep3nXkeimCks7BdAK9Zxq01q2K1UMXbbl_7LScG-2qNu03Z0oEw8B5aX_OgqG3ai3o86JoimTeIPrZA-cVdYhyQNuBrBNANzMwS7qZk14lYT6UxaAHn0Fs1OGS2EHt-NzT2tHKVOgR0vDqlf0eGLozgdnWNbI_C7y2LwsFH5Gu00PO6RQ8sK__UWtmmrYDO9BcPGBKTXuM10wMNGGkogSvlUebeAcpKZtA8UfRcQQ6Lq1IZzKfAu2RmFM9kTGj9G4og8KJAtncTWq3EvOhExkhv7Yh0g7NfGCNxjK1-B2b7tG1FT1Khrx9_49rhUw0WzQnzAMEX7lcgMXiIj-LeEuTyYuJkzzcsQBp7rxgdFuyUPF3gkoktGFKgd_jR30ZRv_Kf-6qEDiWesrTObcCMgcTCenrxlU5WRBaijZXcg1kkHAmcGMuozv24Heuq344I3Wa5z7dqIYYA60SWT2gsJYJuYx9d-71q2SRgIT6TaKH1Aqddp3vxdzBKysJqLce7qUs4SHq9Wo9bmx054VfKuwog6Dg-gWC6KH7KWwn-qH7Ycip2cO_9hJlVhoRbl3BoGbfDeAyb4DzcjuSE2GAFqtOw9NXMO8ewjHAjw43AFiHQBqlQzfbh1EqYUdf68Wm7BhvDD7eyWv7J1jd4D2hnQBeXNYaLFtlUywK64QHJ3o-_ZyW7AEQC79ZsNk4pHjJnL0C6f3uRgDt2fIrWURbAhCJSppmi4lf2Juj3Zw5R67tBrBkjiaIx9kDkGirViteKjZ2CnIz10ls5srpjtFpXyBBWiYtqMf3-1vlf97mfE1CGog5-oY7xuzcYZ3ATCXASOjyNfDmrs-CJ4kITfWVmAV6C