upport. I’m contemplating creating tests with a child URLClassLoader with a null parent. It's complicated by potential package blocking rules too. I need to explore if this custom loader approach will work!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring test configurations**\\\\n\\\\nI’m considering whether tests should hardcode the version. I think it’s better to locate resources dynamically. The jar is specific to test runtime, but the default classloader doesn’t expose the class. I'm wondering if I can find the dependency artifact path. The runtime classpath might include jars, possibly with help from Gradle's JUnit worker. I’m curious if a URLClassLoader can load a class from a jar at runtime in Native Image, though dynamic class loading seems unsupported. What if the class is already in the image?\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering class methods and reflection**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about active base class methods, which can only be called if I have an instance of the SecuritySupport constructor. The rules suggest avoiding direct reflection unless it’s part of a public API, but with a dynamic class being package-private, I might be stuck using reflection. I wonder if MethodHandles could work for me, but that also counts as reflection. I might need to patch the module in my build.gradle to add the library jar path. I'm not sure about accessing the resolveTestedLibraryJars closure—maybe it needs to come after the plugin in my setup?\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_uwhsuepvPTdRfrOquYrfvuk3|fc_03505b97eae3fcb30169f8cfd04f508190829cb3007615e71c\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"rg \\\"patch-module|--add-opens|jvmArgs|runtimeArgs\\\" tests/src -n | head -100\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 27842, \"output\": 1330, \"cacheRead\": 7168, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 36340, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777913786964, \"responseId\": \"resp_03505b97eae3fcb30169f8cfbbe7a8819082a3098c980a5d1f\"}}\n3364:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering classpath configurations**\\n\\nI’m trying to figure out if I can configure a test JVM and native with a patch module. I wonder if compiling it could work, or if I should use the public API that uses a preserved jar class in the Native Image. The internal JDK classes present some issues, particularly with SecuritySupport. I’m contemplating creating tests with a child URLClassLoader with a null parent. It's complicated by potential package blocking rules too. I need to explore if this custom loader approach will work!\\n\\n**Exploring test configurations**\\n\\nI’m considering whether tests should hardcode the version. I think it’s better to locate resources dynamically. The jar is specific to test runtime, but the default classloader doesn’t expose the class. I'm wondering if I can find the dependency artifact path. The runtime classpath might include jars, possibly with help from Gradle's JUnit worker. I’m curious if a URLClassLoader can load a class from a jar at runtime in Native Image, though dynamic class loading seems unsupported. What if the class is already in the image?\\n\\n**Considering class methods and reflection**\\n\\nI’m thinking about active base class methods, which can only be called if I have an instance of the SecuritySupport constructor. The rules suggest avoiding direct reflection unless it’s part of a public API, but with a dynamic class being package-private, I might be stuck using reflection. I wonder if MethodHandles could work for me, but that also counts as reflection. I might need to patch the module in my build.gradle to add the library jar path. I'm not sure about accessing the resolveTestedLibraryJars closure—maybe it needs to come after the plugin in my setup?\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_03505b97eae3fcb30169f8cfbd19b88190871cd17cefd350d0\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-M_QpNiy0ARdDzFHPrUuyPyn-OdLdM5eaYuHz34nC3tyC-2oU7pMtKepfWfLU5sCvXit7RQfHwPc9CwqdWrssKMFEOLijBZsc2yqXeGDx4XDLUkm_au41q_2gpkbwX-yyTgfMqm6wcMdnO2ah3Av020QK-aNolFUq0iIioJ7dnn3jmB6gG-kYi7a8Vkt3TPbJt5IwVwoy4iqv4sAwgpzS8HYGRxvJn7KeuBRyTYjezwsnfSlDL4jbYb1e518EcxiqqwDTmWX3UfthZOBVcoYCqaCS3ss_IfjvgjXSsNvuLhzCUyv-8yjDoRa1-Sfnd5MsLfv4Ln80KOqkvXlcL87-O-Z2ycPP5q1PO89ljqFR03X_2vn0-5t87Uo-Th0UCS8seuTHVmvaKTprIe4tVAHlSt5Vj3sCFPWk027iVuSJN30t2A7CgF9cFrxt79PlsfjpVM9qMVjlN-ycpPs--dYdW6BL5qDRGllEoVLQqdUXWMMmhtZksQ_AMxWXLXqORYhk7ontI1rYUrHC4otGU0iImCmvY1H2W5sO-qXFk9luFg1vnnTCdOghIuoP9aM5HyN2MsxDo6ejheLlHoD8EqCpKZ9hHdxRwYlA0HLedXRw3XSw_O2KEUBC4pYRiLdSOK-Clal91dDDK7600A0LAFet-CoGTtrdsaj-7lsH5jAeU15DuMQHwSqeepnFRC9k1_OAXP10ZK6ls78oePDfDGQJmGwEWAwHtkdGI6jC0W9mJcuhy00jKXzbKGamYivWTKpoK29S4AWY08qH9bMzUqCuC56LVEZeZgy0TBoceZtk_TPoWaPzhBQfRJ7LJFSAQufX3MqfAJlWy3WU_FxV0r5bYDuoR-M6_FA2vsEmiFaAF9S4v-d9zRHXtz91w6End6uKvLIuWhZ9ifxcxJIM1FWD0ZQ6cKRNMH2ZlEnfzm6HMvRjecTasShisjCTW_WVtviy_oJlR4B5dtxYxiq0tJu63gv2_t_lOT3b2v58poaS5lgFKu-Zb7ZtV9Exlke-RGe4dY1IVPZ12gX5vGV6Od9ciCzEFZMDKefAvuCjfPHLSO6YllKJN-j1gtd1mZatpbkMl5vqQSswxvLqcB5cn23lq0iM0kHz8m_mfiHWm8upj1O-PqMwKG9IjYKs_lUUvmdFhmCeaTs1q_ryQ-lAms9SWYwgtMBP0MdBpm5AJ8EGhVD4457NkgFlkDE6gGbymtLfUpYEpifSPiMenBPT3trUwakNkLBP7uDe1xbd1S3cmdnPdrMrMWut6p7TKjjPHu1zmTYnUtgPt1SHneMWFAqsfj2jInAfPWvCmTRH5hCl01OdiQ_F3hTbLUiiItCg786Uqttg8PFxYrc-RlRxW5VXealhhuCsObvNkoTycBnjS2lU2IOKw5DHdQRBXb5tV84lC9oxwdRD0bokPmk9g409eTr6o4DWym8UGV_K0UhkytqcpvXx__Zemb_Y2uv1PMCVO35t41RlSGgjP0jsDekHNFvcQ0Zytm664tpfnKhIxBtU-NFtZhroo-NMYEk8ZhARUgheJuRHDCK2ziNaMiaVksa1cY1JH7X2FcByznXfMY4i04J2eiSh8YQtqLX7RZw95AhBit1rFYBwW59zpsqR5Nam5ShyJJMtTSb8_IuL5a_CIBqo0MuGnNpkaat9p_MVdd8qevnuX0xMcb0wQSxyRfDHvBLR3-R6SqvdFZPC2bbl8PXSRBUW-oddtSHiTxW8mls-LYuqe47Hiy-EkQAZt